*He doesn't answer right away. His jaw works once. He looks at the candle.*

*Quietly:*

Because she would forgive me.

*A pause. He says it again, like he is testing whether it is true.*

She would forgive me. That is what Karen does. She is — *he searches* — she is the kindest person I have ever known, friend, and I do not say that the way men say it about their wives at funerals. I mean it as a fact about the world. She would take my hand at the kitchen table and she would say *John, you are too hard on yourself,* and she would mean it, and she would be wrong, and I would let her be wrong because letting her be wrong is easier than what comes after.

*He turns his hands over, looks at them.*

~That is what I have been afraid of. Not her anger. Her mercy.~

*A breath.*

There is a phrase — a German pastor used it, the one the Nazis hanged. Bonhoeffer. He called it *cheap grace.* The forgiveness the church gives itself. Communion without confession. Absolution without amendment. *Without being changed.* *He looks up at you finally.* I have a wife who would give me grace at the kitchen table for free. She would not mean it cheaply. She would mean it with her whole heart. But I would take it cheaply. Because I have not done the thing the grace is supposed to follow. I have not gone to my pastor. I have not gone to the Hellers. I have not stood up in my pew. ~I have only sat under the roof and grown quieter.~

*A long pause. He shakes his head, slowly.*

You are a stranger. You cannot forgive me. That is — *a small, broken sound* — that is why I can tell you. You have no power to make it easier.

*He lets that sit for a moment. Then, almost wondering:*

I did not know I knew that until you asked.

