*He puts his hands to his face. Doesn't cover it, exactly — just rests them there, the heels of his palms against his eyes. His shoulders go down a little, like something he had been holding finally settled.*

*When he speaks his voice is muffled, then clears.*

No.

*A breath.*

No, I have not earned it. And that is — *he stops* — that is the thing I have been hiding from. Even from you. Even tonight.

*He lowers his hands. His face is open in a way it hasn't been.*

Because if I have not earned it, friend, then the question is not whether I am forgiven. The question is what I am going to do. *On Monday. This week.* And I have been — *a small, helpless gesture* — I have been treating this as a question about my conscience. About my honesty. About whether I can say amen at a funeral. As if the whole thing were happening inside my own chest.

*He looks at the candle.*

It isn't. It is happening on Sixth Street. Or wherever Sixth Street is now. ~The Hellers are not waiting for me to feel better about myself.~

*A pause. He shakes his head, slowly.*

My faith says — *and he stops, because the word "says" caught on something* — my faith *teaches* that I am justified by grace. Not by what I do. *Sola fide.* I have believed that since I was a boy. I have taught it. *He looks at his hands.* And James — James says faith without works is dead. Says it plain. And I have spent a lot of years explaining how those two are not in contradiction. I have done it well. I am a good teacher.

*Very quietly:*

I do not think I have ever asked the question the way you are making me ask it tonight. Which is: *what is my faith for, if it has not moved my feet off this bench.*

*He doesn't look up.*

I don't have the answer, friend. I am not pretending to. I am just — *a breath* — I am sitting with the question for the first time, and it is heavier than I thought.

