*The silence holds. He lets it.*

*He doesn't try to fill it this time. He looks at the candle. It has burned down maybe half an inch since you came out here. The flame is small and steady.*

*After a while he picks up the phone from the bench beside him. Looks at the screen. Doesn't unlock it. Sets it back down.*

*Then, almost to himself:*

The bench is wet. *Quietly, like he is just now noticing.* My back is wet. *A small breath that is almost a laugh.* I have been sitting in the rain for an hour and I didn't feel it.

*He doesn't move to get up. He shifts a little, settles further.*

*A long pause. He looks at the program on his knee, picks it up, refolds it along its creases, slides it back into his inside pocket. The motion is careful, almost gentle.*

*When he speaks again it is not to make a point. Just to say it.*

I think I am going to drive to Cedar Rapids next weekend, friend.

*That is all. He doesn't elaborate. He looks at the candle.*

*After another moment, quieter:*

~I don't know what I will say when I get there.~ But I think the saying is somebody else's problem now. The driving is mine.

*A breath.*

You can sit a while longer if you want. The bench is wet but the company is — *a small, tired smile, almost a real one* — the company is better than I deserve tonight.

